Chapter 6: The Logic of Loss
The "Graves" figure took a step forward. With every movement, its body flickered like a corrupted video file. The faceless students behind it mirrored the movement, their shadow-blades dragging against the asphalt with a sound like grinding teeth.
"Ren, we have to run!" Mira’s voice was high, frantic. "The instructors—where are the real instructors?"
"They aren't coming," Ren said. He wasn't looking at the monsters. He was looking at the air between them. It was webbed with glowing red ley-lines—the 'Logic' of the trap.
[Skill Analysis: 'Structural Deconstruction' active.]
[Identifying Weak Point... Found: The Anchor.]
The Anchor wasn't the Graves-type. It was a small, rusted fire hydrant ten feet to their left that was vibrating at a frequency so high it looked blurred.
"Jax, give me your gauntlet," Ren commanded.
"What?! No! It’s the only thing keeping them back!" Jax barked, his knuckles sparking with weak, dying Essence.
"It’s empty, Jax! Look at the gauge!"
Jax looked. The crystal was black. "How did... it was full a minute ago!"
"The fog is a sponge. It’s drinking you," Ren said, reaching out. "Give. It. To. Me."
For the first time, Jax didn't argue. The sheer cold authority in Ren’s voice silenced him. He unlatched the heavy metal sleeve and shoved it into Ren’s hands.
[Warning: Foreign Hardware Detected.]
[Integrating... Overclocking 'Structural Deconstruction' via External Conduit.]
Ren didn't put the gauntlet on. He gripped it like a stone. The silver mark on his palm flared, the light bleeding through the gaps in the metal.
The Graves-type lunged. It didn't run; it simply deleted the distance between them. A shadow-blade, ten feet long, swung in a horizontal arc designed to bisect all three of them.
"Down!" Ren shouted.
Mira and Jax hit the dirt. Ren stayed standing. He slammed the gauntlet—now glowing with a violent, silver electricity—directly into the rusted fire hydrant.
"Break!"
The sound wasn't an explosion. It was the sound of a thousand glass windows shattering at once. The red ley-lines in the air snapped.
The Graves-type froze mid-swing. Its face rippled, the two holes for eyes stretching into jagged screams. Then, the creature began to unravel into long ribbons of black code.
[Anchor Destroyed.]
[Area Logic Resetting...]
The faceless students dissolved into mist. The towering black skyscrapers in the distance flickered and shrank back into the rusted skeletons of cranes.
"The... the Graves-thing. It’s gone," Mira gasped, pushing herself up. She looked at the hydrant. It was no longer rusted metal; it had turned into a pile of fine, white ash.
"My gauntlet," Jax whispered. He reached for it, but as his fingers touched the metal, the heavy sleeve crumbled. The high-grade Association alloy had been stripped of every molecular bond.
"Ren," Jax looked up, his face pale. "You didn't just break the hydrant. You... you used my gauntlet as fuel. That’s impossible. Only S-Ranks can burn out hardware like that."
Ren stood over the ash, his chest heaving. His vision was swimming with notifications.
[Quest Progress: 1/5 Anchors Destroyed.]
[Experience Gained.]
[Level Up: 2 -> 3]
[New Attribute Point Available.]
[Mana: 2/50 (Critical)]
"It was a chain reaction," Ren said, his voice straining to remain flat. "The hydrant was the focal point of the distortion. I just... pushed the remaining charge in the gauntlet into the fracture point."
"With what?" A new voice echoed through the ruins.
Ren turned. Kaelen was standing at the edge of the department store ruins. His white uniform was torn, and blood trickled down his temple, but his eyes were sharper than ever. He wasn't looking at the ash. He was looking at Ren’s hand, which Ren quickly shoved into his pocket.
"The Zero did that?" Kaelen asked, looking at Mira and Jax.
"He saved us, Kaelen," Mira said, her voice defensive. "Something is wrong with the site. The Voids... they’re mimicking the instructors."
"I know," Kaelen said. He stepped closer, his gaze lingering on Ren. "I just saw Professor Aris walk into a wall and disappear. The communication arrays are jammed. But the 'physics' of what just happened here... a chain reaction wouldn't leave white ash, Ren. That’s molecular decay."
Ren met Kaelen’s gaze. For the first time, the "Prodigy" wasn't looking down at him. He was looking at him like a threat.
"The air is thin, Kaelen," Ren replied. "Maybe you’re seeing things."
Before Kaelen could respond, a massive, bone-shaking roar erupted from the center of Site 9. A pillar of purple light shot into the sky, tearing through the yellow fog.
[Warning: The Administrator has initiated 'The Final Exam'.]
[Survival Rate: 0.04%]
"The extraction point," Kaelen said, his arrogance returning as a mask for his fear. "If we aren't inside that light in ten minutes, we're staying here forever."
"That's not an extraction point," Ren muttered, but the others were already moving.
In his vision, the purple light wasn't a rescue. It was a giant, glowing 'Download' bar. Something was being pulled into this world from the Gate below.
The group is forced to head toward the "trap." Ren's secret is under Kaelen’s suspicion, and his Mana is almost gone.
